<Page x:Class="AsynAwaitExamples.Steps.Step10_ConfigureAwait"
      xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml/presentation"
      xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2006/xaml"
      Title="Step 10 - ConfigureAwait">
    <ScrollViewer VerticalScrollBarVisibility="Auto">
        <StackPanel Margin="10">
            <TextBlock Style="{StaticResource HeaderStyle}" 
                       Text="Step 10: ConfigureAwait, Task.Run, and Thread Awareness"/>

            <TextBlock Style="{StaticResource ExplanationStyle}" xml:space="preserve">THREADS: Understanding where your code runs after await.

By default, "await" in a WPF app captures the current thread (UI thread) and
returns to it after the awaited task completes. This is why you can update UI
controls after await without any issues.

But sometimes you want to do CPU-heavy work WITHOUT occupying the UI thread.
That is where Task.Run comes in - it runs code on a background thread.

Key rules:
- After "await", code resumes on the UI thread (by default in WPF).
- Inside Task.Run, code runs on a background thread (cannot touch UI!).
- ConfigureAwait(false): after await, do NOT return to the UI thread.
  Use this in library code that does not need the UI thread.</TextBlock>

            <Button Style="{StaticResource ActionButton}"
                    Content="Show thread IDs (UI thread vs background)"
                    Click="ShowThreads_Click"/>
            <Button Style="{StaticResource ActionButton}"
                    Content="CPU-heavy work with Task.Run"
                    Click="TaskRun_Click"/>

            <TextBox x:Name="Output" Style="{StaticResource OutputStyle}" Height="280"/>
        </StackPanel>
    </ScrollViewer>
</Page>
